Your backend is healthy, so this is now a frontend-to-backend URL issue.

The problem is here:

const res = await fetch(`${BACKEND_URL}/matches/upcoming`);
Your frontend is probably trying to call the wrong host from inside Next.js.

Why this happens
Inside Docker:

backend container is reachable as http://backend:8000

from your browser, backend is reachable as http://localhost:8000

So there are two different URLs depending on where the code runs.

Because your Next.js page is doing server-side fetch behavior, localhost:8000 from inside the frontend container does not mean your backend container.

Fix it
Option 1: easiest fix for now
Change frontend/lib/api.ts to hardcode backend service name:

export const BACKEND_URL = "http://backend:8000";

export async function getUpcomingMatches() {
  const res = await fetch(`${BACKEND_URL}/matches/upcoming`);
  return res.json();
}

export async function getPrediction(matchId: number, stage: string, modelUri: string) {
  const url = new URL(`${BACKEND_URL}/predictions/match/${matchId}`);
  url.searchParams.set("stage", stage);
  url.searchParams.set("model_uri", modelUri);
  const res = await fetch(url.toString());
  return res.json();
}
Then rebuild frontend:

docker compose up --build frontend
Option 2: cleaner fix
Use two env vars:

In .env:

NEXT_PUBLIC_BACKEND_URL=http://localhost:8000
INTERNAL_BACKEND_URL=http://backend:8000
Then in frontend/lib/api.ts:

const BACKEND_URL =
  process.env.INTERNAL_BACKEND_URL || process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_BACKEND_URL || "http://backend:8000";

export async function getUpcomingMatches() {
  const res = await fetch(`${BACKEND_URL}/matches/upcoming`);
  if (!res.ok) {
    throw new Error(`Failed to fetch upcoming matches: ${res.status}`);
  }
  return res.json();
}

export async function getPrediction(matchId: number, stage: string, modelUri: string) {
  const url = new URL(`${BACKEND_URL}/predictions/match/${matchId}`);
  url.searchParams.set("stage", stage);
  url.searchParams.set("model_uri", modelUri);

  const res = await fetch(url.toString());
  if (!res.ok) {
    throw new Error(`Failed to fetch prediction: ${res.status}`);
  }
  return res.json();
}
