so now you need historical data ingestion

Next step: test the ETL container
Run this now:

docker compose --profile ops run --rm etl python -m etl.cli --help
If that works, your ETL service is build-ready.

After that: create a local raw data folder
In your project root, create:

mkdir data
mkdir data\cricsheet
So your structure becomes:

ipl-predictor/
  data/
    cricsheet/
Then: get IPL historical files into that folder
Put your historical IPL source files into:

data/cricsheet
For now, even one or two match files is enough for a smoke test.

One likely thing you need to add
Your current docker-compose.yml probably does not mount the local data folder into the ETL container yet.

Under the etl: service, add:

volumes:
  - ./data:/data
So ETL can read:

/data/cricsheet
You may also want the same mount on trainer later:

volumes:
  - ./data:/data
After that, run ingestion
Once files exist in data/cricsheet, run:

docker compose --profile ops run --rm etl python -m etl.cli ingest-cricsheet /data/cricsheet
What success should look like
After ingestion, this should no longer be zero:

docker compose exec postgres psql -U ipl_user -d ipl_db -c "SELECT COUNT(*) FROM matches;"
And you should also check:

docker compose exec postgres psql -U ipl_user -d ipl_db -c "SELECT COUNT(*) FROM teams;"
docker compose exec postgres psql -U ipl_user -d ipl_db -c "SELECT COUNT(*) FROM players;"
docker compose exec postgres psql -U ipl_user -d ipl_db -c "SELECT COUNT(*) FROM ball_by_ball;"
Important note
Your ETL command may still fail, because the starter code I gave earlier included a CLI skeleton but not the full Cricsheet parser implementation yet. That is normal.

