Thought for 16s
You’ve trained the model; the remaining failure is MLflow server security config.

MLflow 3.5.0+ added host-header and CORS protection. When the server runs in Docker and receives requests with host mlflow:5000, it can reject them unless that host is explicitly allowed. MLflow documents this under --allowed-hosts / MLFLOW_SERVER_ALLOWED_HOSTS, and notes the exact "Invalid Host header - possible DNS rebinding attack detected" error for this case. 

Fix docker-compose.yml
Update your mlflow: service to include allowed hosts and CORS origins.

Use something like this:

  mlflow:
    image: ghcr.io/mlflow/mlflow:v3.5.0
    command: >
      mlflow server
      --host 0.0.0.0
      --port 5000
      --backend-store-uri sqlite:///mlflow.db
      --default-artifact-root /mlruns
      --allowed-hosts "mlflow,localhost,127.0.0.1"
      --cors-allowed-origins "http://localhost:3000,http://localhost:5000"
    ports:
      - "5000:5000"
    volumes:
      - ./ml/mlruns:/mlruns
      - ./ml/mlflow:/mlflow
    profiles: ["ml"]
A few notes:

mlflow is needed because your trainer container talks to the MLflow service by that Docker service name.

localhost and 127.0.0.1 are needed because you open the UI in the browser at http://localhost:5000.

MLflow’s docs say --allowed-hosts controls accepted Host headers, and --cors-allowed-origins controls browser origins. 

